No one in their right minds would ever think that would actually occur over say robots being made as servants in the future. Sure... let's take a wild animal with 5x our strength and turn them into domestic servants. Stupid. If humanity did that it would deserve to get wiped out. Of course that is exactly WHY the writers of these crappy screenplays did it.   Of course in reality MAN is the most deadly creature on this planet by a factor of like 1000. So yeah... apes... toast IRL.

text: *When they reach the point of the original film, they should cast Michael Fassbender as a young Charlton Heston.*  Also, don't correct me about this being a different timeline. The creators' intention was always to lead up to the 1968 film.  If you've done your homework and want to challenge me with these points: -The Icarus spacecraft is seen leaving earth in Rise, which contradicts the ship leaving in 1972 A.D. in the original film: That was just an easter egg at a time when they weren't sure if they'd have so many sequels. If it were truly a vital plot point that it left recently instead of in 1972, they would have made the scene more clearly. -Nova appears in War when she's supposed to meet Taylor in 3978 A.D.: That's clearly not the same Nova because her hair and skin is the wrong tone, she is fully aware of intelligent humans and she receives her name by happy coincidence. -Caesar died before ever fighting Aldo: Aldo is cited in Ape scripture in the original film, but the scripture never said that he'd met Caesar. That's only a product of the largely improvised sequels, which are not canon anymore. As Caesar was the Ape equivalent of Moses, likely Aldo will be the Ape Messiah of their New Testament. Maybe he'll even be responsible for the Statue of Liberty sticking out of the shore like that.  You skeptics are the same people who said that these new films were a full reboot of the original that took things more seriously, which is why we'll probably never see the modern Ape city and the mute humans. And yet the Apes only get more advanced with each film, and they found a realistic way to make humans mute again. Why would they do that if it weren't a prequel to the original?  Please, challenge me on this from any angle.

text: The story of Caesar   In "Rise of the Planet of the Apes" we see a young boy. He's innocent, and still learning, but we watch him grow up. He's become intelligent and has developed his own personality. His life starts to spiral down, and everything he knew started to crumple away, we watch him learn about the world and see him start something that would change the world. In "Dawn of the Planet of the Apes, years pass and we see this boy has grown into a young king. He has a wife, and two children, he has something to fight for, something important. His conflicting feelings about apes and humans get in the way of his life. He remembers his human father, who taught him, and loved him. He showed compassion and mercy, but the world did not share the same feelings as him. In "War for the Planet of the Apes" we see the boy become into a great king with resolve. He has decided to fight, despite his feelings, he fights. The following quote "No mercy, no peace, this is war" is proof of his resolve, later he states "I did not start this war, but I will finish it." This shows that he is willing to do anything for his family and race, even sacrifice himself.

text: Why do I get an underlying sense that these movies have been, and are foreshadowing current and future events of our nation...   I'll try to blanket the obvious of which demographics we have in major cities across this nation that tend to act out largely with their inherent rhesus+ DNA confirmed genetic traits, moreso than other humans...  I was dating a female at the time when we watched this movie, and I looked at her while watching the movie and had the grand epiphany of how much she resembled these "apes" aesthetics, behavior, everything...  I truly believe this is an underlying prejudice/racist film in the grand scheme of things. You can hear Woody's script in this movie, "We created you" "Now it's time to end your kind"  The apes were "slaves" in these films. They  were "assimilated" by white scientists/people's.  That soldiers helmet said "Monkey Killer" "Hunting down monkeys/apes/guerillas"  We all know which demographics of people are typically singled out when it comes to law enforcement tactics etc.  This nature of this movie is being cleverly subtle with it's message, but the message it's sending is really in plain sight.
